<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch2-First-Order" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>First-Order Differential Equations</title>

<p>
  In this chapter, we shall study first-order order ordinary differential equations that can be written in standard form
  <md xml:id="eq-First-order-general" number="yes">
    y'=f(x,y).
  </md>
</p>

<section xml:id="sec-Intro-to-first-order">
  <title>Introduction to First-Order Differential Equations</title> 


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Part-general-singular">
        <title>Particular, General, and Singular Solutions</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-">
            <title>Particular, General, and Singular Solutions</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   A function <m>y=y(x)</m> is said to be a <term>solution</term> of differential equation <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> on an interval <m>I</m> provided it is differentiable on <m>I</m> and
                </p>
                <md>
                    y'(x)=f\left(x,y(x)\right)\text{ for all }x\in I
                </md>
                <p>
                   A one-parameter family of solutions <m>y=y(x,c)</m> of differential equation <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> containing an arbitrary constant<m>c</m> is called a <term>general solution</term>. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Any particular choice of a specific value for <m>c</m> yields a <term>particular solution</term>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    A first-order differential equation may have both a general solution involving an arbitrary constant<m>c</m> and particular solutions that cannot be obtained from it by any choice of <m>c</m>. Such exceptional solutions are called <term>singular solutions</term>(see Examples <xref ref="example-Singular"/> in Section <xref ref="sec-Separable"/>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    To solve <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> is to find <em>all</em> of its solutions.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <note>
            <p>
                Since a differentiable function is necessarily continuous, every solution <m>y=y(x)</m> of <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> on an interval <m>I</m> must be continuous on <m>I</m>.
            </p>
        </note>
        <p>
            For a first-order equation of the form
        </p>
        <md>
            y'=f(x),
        </md>
        <p>
            where <m>f(x)</m> is a continuous function on an interval <m>I</m>, a
            <term>general solution</term> on <m>I</m> is
        </p>
        <md>
            y=\int f(x)\,dx=F(x)+c\qquad (c\in \R),
        </md>
        <p>
            where <m>F(x)</m> is an antiderivative of <m>f</m> on <m>I</m>.
            By the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (see, e.g., <xref ref="Stewart"/> ),
            we can set
        </p>
        <md>
            F(x):=\int_{x_0}^{x}f(t)\,dt,\quad x\in I,
        </md>
        <p>
            where <m>x_{0}</m> is a fixed point in <m>I</m>.
        </p>

        <example>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The one-parameter family <m>y=c</m> ( <m>c\in \R</m> ) is a general
                        solution of the equation.
                    </p>
                    <md>
                        y'=0
                    </md>

                    <p>
                        on <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        The one-parameter family <m>y=\ln|x|+c</m> ( <m>c \in \R</m> ) is
                        the general solution of the equation.
                    </p>
                    <md>
                        y'=\dfrac{1}{x}
                    </md>

                    <p>
                        on each of the intervals <m>(-\infty,0)</m> and <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>        
        </example>

    </subsection>

<subsection>
    <title>Initial Value Problems</title>

    <definition>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Initial Value Problem
            </p>

            <p>
                A first-order differential equation <xref ref="F-ODE"/> is often
                accompanied by a condition of the form:
            </p>
            <md>
                y(x_{0})=y_{0},
            </md>

            <p>
                where <m>x_{0}</m> and <m>y_{0}</m> are specified values.
                Such a condition is called an <em>initial condition</em> (IC)
                and such a problem
            </p>
            <md>
                y'=f(x,y),\ y(x_{0})=y_{0}
            </md>

            <p>
                is called an <em>initial value problem</em> (IVP).
            </p>

            <p>
                A solution of the initial value problem <xref ref="IVP"/> is a
                function <m>y=y(x)</m> satisfying both the differential equation
                on some interval <m>I</m> containing <m>x_{0}</m> and the
                initial condition.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        One way to solve initial value problem <xref ref="IVP"/> is to
    </p>

    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    first find the general solution <m>y=y(x,c)</m> of the
                    equation, which, provided the differential equation is of
                    the form
                </p>
                <md>
                    y'=f(x),
                </md>

                <p>
                    can be done via indefinite integration
                </p>
                <md>
                    y=\int f(x)\,dx,
                </md>

                <p>
                    and
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    then, plug <m>x = x_{0}</m> and <m>y = y_{0}</m> into the
                    general solution, and solve for <m>c</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <example xml:id="EXMP2">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the initial value problem
            </p>
            <md>
                y'=\dfrac{1}{x},\ y(1)=0.
            </md>

            <p>
                <alert>Solution:</alert> Considering that the initial
                <m>x</m>-value 1 is in the interval <m>(0,\infty)</m>, where
                <m>|x|=x</m>, we obtain the unique solution of the IVP from the
                general solution <m>y=\ln|x|+c=\ln x+c</m> of the equation on
                <m>(0,\infty)</m> by substituting the values <m>x=1</m> and
                <m>y=0</m> into it:
            </p>
            <md>
                0=\ln 1+c,
            </md>

            <p>
                which yields <m>c = 0</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Thus, the unique solution to the IVP on <m>(0,\infty)</m> is
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \boxed{y=\ln x.}
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
        An alternative <em>definite-integral approach</em> to solving an initial
        value problem of the form
    </p>
    <md>
        y'=f(x),\ y(x_{0})=y_{0},
    </md>

    <p>
        which bypasses finding the general solution of the differential
        equation, is based on the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus and, provided
        the function <m>f(x)</m> is continuous on an interval <m>I</m>
        containing <m>x_{0}</m>, gives the <em>unique</em> solution of the IVP
        by the formula
    </p>
    <md>
        y=y_{0}+\int_{x_0}^{x}f(t)\,dt.
    </md>

    <p>
        In the following examples, we will compare the two approaches to solving
        initial value problem <xref ref="IVPS"/>.
    </p>
    Solve the following initial value problems.
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>y'=x\sqrt{x^{2}+9},\ y(-4)=0</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <alert>Solution:</alert> (indefinite integral approach)
            </p>

            <p>
                First, we find the general solution of the equation
            </p>
            <md>
                y&amp;= \int x \sqrt{x^{2} + 9}\, dx \\  \intertext{Using substitution ($u = x^{2} + 9$, so $du = 2x \, dx$), we obtain}y&amp;= \frac{1}{3}(x^{2} + 9)^{\frac{3}{2}}+ c.
            </md>

            <p>
                Next, we need to determine the value of <m>c</m> for which the
                solution we have obtained will satisfy the IVP.
            </p>

            <p>
                Substituting in the initial condition gives
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \dfrac{1}{3}\left((-4)^{2}+9\right)^{3/2}+c=0,
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                which we solve to find <m>c=-\dfrac{125}{3}</m>.
                The unique solution is, therefore,
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \boxed{y = \dfrac{1}{3}(x^2+9)^{3/2}-\dfrac{125}{3},}
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                or
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \boxed{y = \dfrac{1}{3}\left((x^2+9)^{3/2}-125\right).}
                </md>
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                <m>y'=xe^{-x},\ y(0)=1</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <alert>Solution:</alert> (definite-integral approach)
            </p>

            <p>
                The desired solution is given by the formula
            </p>
            <md>
                y=1+\int_{0}^{x}te^{-t}\,dt.
            </md>

            <p>
                Integrating by parts, with
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \begin{array}{ll}u =t,&amp;du =dt\\

dv = e^{-t}\,dt,&amp; v=-e^{-t},\end{array}
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                we have:
            </p>
            <md>
                \int_{0}^{x}te^{-t}\,dt&amp;= \left[\left.-te^{-t}\right|_{0}^{x}+\int_{0}^{x} e^{-t}\,dt\right] \\&amp;=\left[\left.-xe^{-x}-e^{-t}\right|_{0}^{x}\right] \\&amp;=\left[-xe^{-x}-(e^{-x}-1)\right]\\&amp;=-xe^{-x}-e^{-x}+1=-(x+1)e^{-x}+1.
            </md>

            <p>
                Therefore, the solution is
                <md>
                    \boxed{y(x)=-(x+1)e^{-x}+2.}
                </md>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</subsection>

<subsection>
    <title>Exercises for Section <xref ref="introd"/></title>

    <p>
        Find a general solution of the following equations.
    </p>

    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\ds y' = xe^{-x^2}</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}= 3x^{2}\sin(x^{3})</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}= 4e^{t} \cos(t)</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>

    <p>
        Solve the following initial value problems.
    </p>

    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\ds y' = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{x+2}}, \ y(2)=-1</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\ds y' = (t^{2} + 2t + 1)e^{t}, \ y(0) = 2</m>
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\ds \frac{dy}{dx}= \dfrac{\ln(x)}{x}, \ y(1) = 0 \quad (x &gt; 0)</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
</subsection>

</section>

</chapter>

